Add a New vmbr in Proxmox for Internal Networking
Initial setup:
 * Proxmox Host IP: 10.10.10.x/24
 * Main Gateway (Proxmox Host) 10.10.10.x
 * Target Internal Network for CT: 192.175.1.x/24 (gateway: 192.175.1.x)
 * vmbr0 is already used for the main access, so we will create vmbr1 for CT Internal Network.

1. Create vmb1 in Proxmox Web UI
 a. Log in to Proxmox Web UI
 b. Go to Server Host --> Network --> Create --> Linux Bridge
 c. Fill in: 
	* Name: vmbr1
	* Bridge ports: empty
	* save

2. Edit Host Network Configuration
 Edit /etc/network/interfaces --> Add the following at the command:
 auto vmbr1
 iface vmbr1 inet static
	address 192.175.1.x/24 
	bridge-port none
	bridge-stp off
	bridge-fd 0
For CT gateway

3. Active vmbr1, Restart and Check Interfaces
# bash
ifup vmbr1
systemctl restart netwroking
ip addr show vmbr1

4. Enable IP Forwarding on Proxmox Host and Apply changes
Edit /etc/sysctl.conf and set
net.ipv4.ip_forward=1
# bash
sysctl -p

5. Set Up NAT and check
If CT internet access goes trough vmbr0 (10.10.10.x), run: 
# bash
iptables -t nat -A POSTROUTING -s 192.175.1.0/24 -o vmbr0 -j MASQUERADE
iptables -t nat -L -n -v

6. Create CT and Configure Networking
 a. Create a new CT --> Assign IP 192.175.1.x/24
 b. Set CT gateway = vmbr1 IP on Proxmox Host (192.175.1.1)
 c. Check routing:
# bash 
ip route show
 d. If no default route exists, add it:
# bash
ip route add default via 192.175.1.1

7. Test Internet Access
# bash 
ping google.com
